Looking for an Alternative to Radical Islamism? -- t9. “Our Vanished Lady”: Memory, Ritual, and Shiʿi-Sunni Relations at Bībī Pāk Dāman -- tCommentary on Part III: The Problems and Perils of Translating Sufism as “Moderate Islam” -- tPart IV. Sufism in Indian National Spaces -- t10. Is All Politics Local? Neighborhood Shrines and Religious Healing in Contemporary India -- t11. Sufi Healing and Secular Psychiatry in India -- t12. Sufi Sound, Sufi Space: Indian Cinema and the Mise-en- Scène of Pluralism -- tCommentary on Part IV: Sufism in Indian National Spaces -- tConclusion: Thinking Otherwise -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tRELIGION, CULTURE, AND PUBLIC LIFE0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSufism is typically thought of as the mystical side of Islam. In recent years, it has been held up as a supposedly peaceful alternative to the spread of forms of Islam associated with violence, an embodiment of democratic ideals of tolerance and pluralism. Are Sufis in fact as otherworldy and apolitical as this stereotype suggests?Modern Sufis and the State brings together a range of scholars, including anthropologists, historians, and religious-studies specialists, to challenge common assumptions that are made about Sufism today. Focusing on India and Pakistan within a broader global context, this book provides locally grounded accounts of how Sufis in South Asia have engaged in politics from the colonial period to the present. Contributors foreground the effects and unintended consequences of efforts to link Sufism with the spread of democracy and consider what roles scholars and governments have played in the making of twenty-first-century Sufism. They critique the belief that Salafism and Sufism are antithetical, offering nuanced analyses of the diversity, multivalence, and local embeddedness of Sufi political engagements and self-representations in Pakistan and India. Essays question the portrayal of Sufi shrines as sites of toleration, peace, and harmony, exploring cases of tension and conflict. A wide-ranging interdisciplinary collection, Modern Sufis and the State is a timely call to think critically about the role of public discourse in shaping perceptions of Sufism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aIslam and politicszSouth Asia. 0aSufisxPolitical activityzSouth Asia. 0aSufismxPolitical aspectszSouth Asia. 7aRELIGION / Islam / Sufi.2bisacsh1 aAnsari, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBasu, Helene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBellamy, Carla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBond, Brian E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorbett, Rosemary R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorbett, Rosemary R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aErnst, Carl W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEwing, Katherine Pratt, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHermansen, Marcia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIngram, Brannon D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLawrence, Bruce B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeyer, Verena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhilippon, Alix, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPratt Ewing, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aQasim Zaman, Muhammad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRao Umashankar, Rachana, eco